#
# Prompts:
# I would like to develop a deeper technical understanding of the llama-server execution path and the GPU
# compute path to truly understand what is happening when I issue a prompt from OpenCode via the API. Since
# llama-server is peer-reviewed and widely adopted, it serves as an excellent reference for how to implement
# computational inference successfully.
#
# Before we get further, I'd like to develop a comprehensive script to
# provide 100% of the source needed for this exercise. I'm happy to iterate on the definition of the script
# until we get it right. Would it help if I provided a list of all of the files in the repository so that you
# may construct a graph analysis of the constituent parts?
#
# It gives us:
#    the source bundle,
#    exact provenance,
#    a complete repo manifest,
#    explicit inclusion/exclusion accounting.
#
# The broader pattern here is:
#    Create a curated source bundle
#    Create metadata that describes what was included and excluded
#    Create a structural map of the code
#    Create a size map of the repository
#    Use the maps to guide deeper semantic analysis
#
# That general workflow scales well to other repos. It turns “please understand this codebase” into a repeatable pipeline:
#
# repository
# -> manifest
# -> architectural candidate list
# -> size analysis
# -> execution-path tracing
# -> synthesized understanding
#
# General method for other repositories
#
# This same process is broadly applicable.
#
# For any repo, I would use this layered method:
# Layer 1: inventory
#
# What files exist?
# Layer 2: candidate graph
#
# Which files appear central by naming, build references, and directory role?
# Layer 3: size profile
#
